.TH NET-VAR 1 "2026-04-29" "net-mgr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
net-var \- read and write the dhcp_vars table (placeholder values)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B net-var list
.RI [ PATTERN ]
.br
.B net-var get
.I NAME
.br
.B net-var set
.I NAME
.I VALUE
.RB [ \-\-notes
.IR TEXT ]
.br
.B net-var remove
.I NAME
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B net-var
manages a small key=value table used at config-generation time. The
canonical use is feeding placeholder substitutions to
.BR net-gen-dnsmasq (1):
the dhcp.master template contains tokens like
.BR DNSH ,
.BR ROUTER_223 ,
.B TFTP_SERVER
that get rewritten to actual IPs (or other strings) before the
generated config is written. Storing them in the DB keeps the values
centralised — every host that runs net-gen-dnsmasq sees the same
substitutions without per-host config drift.
.PP
Like
.BR net-alias (1),
.B net-var
talks to the database directly, so it must run on the host with
.I /root/.my.cnf
or
.IR ~/.my.cnf
holding the
.B [net-mgr]
section.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
\fBlist\fR [\fIPATTERN\fR]
List variables, optionally filtered by a glob pattern (e.g.
.BR ROUTER_* ).
.TP
\fBget\fR \fINAME\fR
Print the value, or exit 1 if there's no such name.
.TP
\fBset\fR \fINAME\fR \fIVALUE\fR [\fB\-\-notes\fR \fITEXT\fR]
Create or update.
.TP
\fBremove\fR \fINAME\fR
Delete one entry. Aliases:
.B rm
and
.BR del .
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Set the master DNS / DHCP server alias:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-var set DNSH 192.168.15.252 --notes "firewall (gateway3)"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Bulk view of router placeholders:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-var list 'ROUTER_*'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Pipe a value into another command:
.RS 4
.nf
.B router=$(net-var get ROUTER_223)
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR net-gen-dnsmasq (1),
.BR net-alias (1),
.BR net-mgr (7)
